# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apollonia-cyrenaica
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] The **365 Crete earthquake** occurred at about sunrise on 21 July 365 in the Eastern Mediterranean, with an assumed epicentre near Crete.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] Geologists today estimate the undersea earthquake to have been a moment magnitude 8.5 or higher.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] It caused widespread destruction in the central and southern Diocese of Macedonia (modern Greece), Africa Proconsularis (northern Libya), Egypt, Cyprus, Sicily, and Hispania (Spain).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] On Crete, nearly all towns were destroyed.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] The earthquake was followed by a tsunami which devastated the southern and eastern coasts of the Mediterranean, particularly Libya, Alexandria, and the Nile Delta, killing thousands and hurling ships 3 km (1.9 mi) inland.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] The quake left a deep impression on the late antique mind, and numerous writers of the time referred to the event in their works.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] Recent (2001) geological studies view the 365 Crete earthquake in connection with a clustering of major seismic activity in the Eastern Mediterranean between the fourth and sixth centuries which may have reflected a reactivation of all major plate boundaries in the region.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] The earthquake is thought to be responsible for an uplift of nine metres (30 feet) of the island of Crete, which is estimated to correspond to a seismic moment of 1×1022 N⋅m (7.4×1021 lbf⋅ft), or 8.6 on the moment magnitude scale.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] An earthquake of such a magnitude exceeds all modern ones known to have affected the region.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] Carbon dating shows that corals on the coast of Crete were lifted ten metres (33 feet) and clear of the water in one massive push.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] This indicates that the tsunami of 365 was generated by an earthquake in a steep fault in the Hellenic Trench near Crete.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] Scientists estimate that such a large uplift is likely to occur only once in 5,000 years; however, the other segments of the fault could slip on a similar scale—and this could happen every 800 years or so.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] Sedimentation increased dramatically in some areas of the Mediterranean Sea, while other areas had coastal sediments moved to deep waters.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] Historians continue to debate whether ancient sources refer to a single catastrophic earthquake in 365, or whether they represent a historical amalgamation of a number of earthquakes occurring between 350 and 450.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] The interpretation of the surviving literary evidence is complicated by the tendency of late antique writers to describe natural disasters as divine responses or warnings to political and religious events.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] In particular, the virulent antagonism between rising Christianity and paganism at the time led contemporary writers to distort the evidence.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] On the whole, however, the relatively numerous references to earthquakes in a time which is otherwise characterized by a paucity of historical records strengthens the case for a period of heightened seismic activity.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] Kourion on Cyprus, for example, is known to have been hit then by five strong earthquakes within a period of eighty years, leading to its permanent destruction.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] Archeological evidence for the particularly devastating effect of the 365 earthquake is provided by a survey of excavations which document the destruction of most late antique towns and cities in the Eastern and Southern Mediterranean around 365.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] In Cyrenaica (northwestern Libya), two coin hoards attest to the destruction: one from Balagrae, recovered beneath the ambulacrum of the Sanctuary Theater of Asclepius, and another from Cyrene, found beneath a late-antique domestic structure south of the Lower Agora.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] Both hoards consist predominantly of small bronze coins minted between 350 and 361, with the latest identifiable coin dating to 364.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] Architectural remains across this region also display earthquake damage.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] In several cases, human skeletal remains were discovered crushed beneath fallen masonry, confirming the sudden and lethal nature of the event.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] Comparable destruction is documented at Ptolemais, where collapsed columns along the *Via Monumentale* and within the palace complex were never fully restored, despite later imperial rebuilding initiatives.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] The remains of inhabitants attempting to flee were discovered in the peristyle pool of the city's Palazzo delle Colonne.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] There is also epigraphic evidence that helps corroborate the structural damage.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] In the necropolis north of Cyrene, a funerary inscription commemorating a woman named Demetria and her son Theodoulos explicitly records their deaths as caused by an earthquake.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] Paleographically, the inscription can be dated to the second half of the 4th century.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] The Roman historian Ammianus Marcellinus described in detail the tsunami that hit Alexandria and other places in the early hours of 21 July 365.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/365-crete-earthquake] The tsunami in 365 was so devastating that the anniversary of the disaster was still commemorated annually at the end of the sixth century in Alexandria as a "day of horror".
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/abonoteichos] Abonoteichos was a town on the coast of Paphlagonia, memorable as the birthplace of the infamous fortuneteller Alexander Abonoteichites, founder of the cult of Glycon, of whom Lucian left an amusing account in the treatise bearing his name.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/abonoteichos] According to Lucian, Alexander petitioned the Roman emperor (probably Antoninus Pius) that the name of his native place should be changed from Abonoteichos to **Ionopolis**; and whether the emperor granted the request or not, we know that the town was called Ionopolis in later times.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/abonoteichos] Not only does this name occur in Marcian of Heraclea and Hierocles, but on coins of the time of Antoninus and Lucius Verus we find the legend Ionopoliton (ΙΩΝΟΠΟΛΙΤΩΝ), as well as Abonoteichiton (ΑΒΩΝΟΤΕΙΧΙΤΩΝ).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/abonoteichos] The modern Turkish name İnebolu is evidently a corruption of Ionopolis.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/abonoteichos] It was the site of a 2nd-century AD temple of Apollo.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/abonoteichos] It was important enough in the Roman province of Paphlagonia to become a suffragan bishopric of the Metropolitan of its capital Gangra, but faded later.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/abonoteichos] The diocese was nominally revived as a Latin Catholic titular bishopric under the name Ionopolis, which was spelled **Jonopolis** in the Roman Curia (besides Italian *Gionopoli*) from 1929 to 1971.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] The **Acarnanian League** (Ancient Greek: τὸ κοινὸν τῶν Ἁκαρνάνων, *to koinon tōn Akarnanōn*) was the tribal confederation, and later a fully-fledged federation (*koinon*), of the Acarnanians in Classical, Hellenistic, and early Roman-era Greece.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] The League existed since the 5th century BC.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] It was at the time not a fully-fledged federation (*sympoliteia*) as elsewhere in Greece, but a loose confederation of the Acarnanian cities.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] An assembly of representatives met at Stratos, having also the power of negotiating treaties with other states, a supreme court existed at Olpae (in common with the Amphilochians), and there was a common coinage and cult, but no federal officials and no common foreign policy.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] The Acarnanians agreed to provide 2,000 hoplites in the common struggle against Philip II of Macedon, but as the latter occupied Ambracia, only a handful volunteers participated alongside the southern Greek city-states in the Battle of Chaeronea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] As a result, the leaders of the independence faction were banished, and the League became a member of the League of Corinth organized by Philip.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] During Alexander the Great's campaign in Asia, the Aetolians seized the town of Oiniadai from the League.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] With the exception of Alyzia, the Acarnanians remained largely uninvolved in the struggles that followed the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BCE, but in 314 BCE Cassander arrived in Acarnania and reorganized the League on a truly federal basis.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] The island of Leucas joined the League soon after, following the eviction of its Macedonian garrison.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] The Acarnanian League was a member of the Hellenic League organized by Demetrius Poliorcetes, and then became subject to King Pyrrhus of Epirus.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] 270 BCE, the Acarnanians and Aetolians settled their differences, agreeing on the Acheloos River as their mutual border, and concluded a perpetual alliance.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] The treaty specified the obligations of mutual military assistance, and the two leagues assured each other the rights of *epigamia*, citizenship, and acquisition of property.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] This treaty records seven *strategoi* (one each from Oiniadai, Derion, Stratos, Phoitia, Thyrreion, Anaktorion and Leucas), a hipparch (from Oiniadai), a foreign secretary (from Oiniadai), and a treasurer (from Stratos).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] The frequent occurrence of officials indicates that at the time it was the most important city of the League.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] According to Polybius, however, soon after the Aetolians allied themselves with Pyrrhus' son.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] Alexander II of Epirus, and invaded Acarnania, dividing the country between them: the northern part with Leucas went to Epirus, and the south was incorporated into the Aetolian League.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] Following the extinction of the Aeacid dynasty in Epirus, in 230 BCE the Acarnanian League was reconstituted in the northern, former Epirote part of the country.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] Leucas was its capital, and only Anaktorion, Palairos, Thyrreion, and Medion were members.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] Allied with the Illyrians, and then with the Macedonians and the Achaean League, in the Social War (220–217 BCE) the Acarnanians were able to recover Phoitia and Oiniadai.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] This success did not last long: in the First Macedonian War (214–205 BCE), Oiniadai was lost again, and in the Second Macedonian War (200–197 BCE) the Acarnanians were forced to capitulate to the Roman Republic, who however left them in their possessions and free to govern themselves.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] Oiniadai was returned after the Roman–Seleucid War.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] Despite their steadfast loyalty to Rome, the League lost Leucas after the Third Macedonian War (171–168 BCE), as it became an autonomous state, but Thyrreion became a member.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] The Acarnanian League continued to exist even after the final establishment of Roman power over Greece in 146 BCE.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/acarnanian-league] It was only after the Battle of Actium in 31 BCE that the League was incorporated into the Roman province of Achaea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The **Achaean League** (Ancient Greek: Κοινὸν τῶν Ἀχαιῶν, romanized: *Koinon ton Akhaion*, lit.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] 'League of Achaeans') was a Hellenistic-era confederation of Greek city-states on the northern and central Peloponnese.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The league was named after the region of Achaea in the northwestern Peloponnese, which formed its original core.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The first league was formed in the fifth century BC.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Although the first Achaean League is much less well documented than its later revival, it maintained a recognizable federal structure through the early Hellenistic period, but later fell into a period of dormancy under growing Macedonian influence.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The more famous second Achaean League was established in 280 BC.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] It allied with Antigonid Macedon at the Cleomenean War, Social War and First Macedonian War against the Aetolian League and Sparta.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Its most successful leader was Philopoemen who forced Sparta to join the League.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The league allied with the Roman Republic during the Second Macedonian War and the Aetolian War.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The Achaean War led to the League's conquest and dissolution by the Romans in 146 BC.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The League represents the most successful attempt by the Greek city-states to develop a form of federalism, which balanced the need for collective action with the desire for local autonomy.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Through the writings of the Achaean historian and statesman Polybius, this structure has had an influence on the constitution of the United States and other modern federal states.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The first Achaean League became active in the fifth century in the northwestern Peloponnese.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Its earliest organizational structure remains partly obscure, but new evidence has illuminated aspects of its government.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] A fragmentary inscription discovered at Aegium, dating to the fourth or possibly the very beginning of the third century BC, attests to a developed federal system that included a *boule* (federal council) and a board of *damiourgoi* (federal magistrates).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The ancient capital of the league was Helike, but after the catastrophic destruction of that city by an earthquake and tsunami in 373 BC, Aegium subsequently assumed that role.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Xenophon's *Hellenica* reports that Achaea underwent a democratic revolution in 367 and the previous ruling class was exiled.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Although it was once widely claimed that Alexander the Great dissolved the Achaean League in 324 BC, the passage in Hypereides (*Against Demosthenes* 18) supposed to reference such a dissolution is now widely understood to be too ambiguous to support that interpretation.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The idea is further undermined by the continued political activity of Achaea and Arcadia during the Lamian War, when they refused to join the Greeks while Boeotia did support Antipater.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The league continued to exist into the early Hellenistic period and is attested in 302 BC, when the Achaeans were listed among the members of the League of Corinth revived by Demetrius Poliorcetes.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] In the years following, Macedonian influence intensified in some Achaean cities while others became ruled by tyrants.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] This period of increasing external control appears to have been linked to Demetrius’ change in policy, signalled by his capture and fortification of Athens in 294 BC, with the planting of garrisons in Achaean cities likely occurring shortly thereafter.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Polybius records that during this time, tyrannies were established in cities such as Ceryneia and Bura, and a garrison was stationed at Aegium.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Despite this interference, there is no indication that the Achaean League was formally dissolved.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Historian Jakob Larsen suggests that the confederacy's federal institutions effectively ceased to operate because so many of its member cities were under external control.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] This state of suspension allowed the league to resume its functions later without the need for significant constitutional changes, suggesting that some mutual understanding among the cities facilitated its reactivation when conditions allowed.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The regional Achaean League was revived in 281/0 BC by the communities of Dyme, Patrae, Pharae and Tritaea, joined in 275 by Aegium, which controlled the important sanctuary of Zeus Homarios.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The league grew quickly to include the entire Achaean heartland, and after a decade it had ten or eleven members.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The key moment for the League's transformation into a major power came in 251, when Aratus, the exiled son of a former magistrate of Sicyon, overthrew the tyranny in his native city and brought it into the Achaean League.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Since the Sicyonians were of Dorian and Ionian origin, their inclusion opened the League for other national elements.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Aratus, then only twenty years old, rapidly became the leading politician of the League.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] In the thirty two years between 245 and his death in 213, Aratus would hold the office of general a total of sixteen times.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] At this time, Central Greece and the Peloponnese were dominated by the Macedonian Kingdom of Antigonus II Gonatas who maintained garrisons at key strategic points such as Chalcis, Piraeus and Acrocorinth, the so-called "fetters of Greece".
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] In other cities of the Peloponnese, namely Argos, Orchomenus, and Megalopolis, Antigonus had installed friendly rulers who were perceived as tyrants by the Achaeans.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Aratus, whose father had been killed by one, called for the liberation of these cities and secured financial support for the League from Ptolemy II of Egypt, an enemy of the Antigonids.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] He then used the money to challenge the Macedonian hold on the Peloponnese.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Aratus' greatest success came when he captured Corinth and the fortress of Acrocorinth in 243 BC in a daring night attack.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] This effectively blocked Macedonian access to the Peloponnese by land, isolating their allies at Megalopolis and Argos.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] In light of this success, a number of Greek communities, including Epidaurus and Megara joined the League and Ptolemy III increased Egypt's support for the Achaeans, being elected as the League's *hegemon* (leader) in return.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Antigonus Gonatas finally made peace with the Achaean League in a treaty of 240 BC, ceding the territories that he had lost in Greece.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The increased size of the league meant a bigger citizen army and more wealth, which was used to hire mercenaries, but it also led to hostility from the remaining independent Greek states, especially Elis, the Aetolian League and Sparta, which perceived the Achaeans as a threat.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Corinth was followed by Megalopolis in 235 BC and Argos in 229 BC.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] However the league soon ran into difficulties with the revived Sparta of Cleomenes III.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Aratus was forced to call in the aid of the Macedonian King, Antigonus III Doson, who defeated Cleomenes at Sellasia.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Antigonus Doson re-established Macedonian control over much of the region.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] In 220 BC, the Achaean League entered into a war against the Aetolian League, which was called the "Social War".
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The young king Philip V of Macedon sided with the Achaeans and called for a Panhellenic conference in Corinth, where the Aetolian aggression was condemned.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] After Aratus's death, however, the League joined Rome in the Second Macedonian War (200–196 BC), which broke Macedonian power in mainland Greece.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The Achaean League was one of the main beneficiaries.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Under the leadership of Philopoemen, the League was able to finally defeat a heavily weakened Sparta and take control of the entire Peloponnese.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The League's dominance was not to last long, however.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] In 146 BC, the league's relations with Rome completely collapsed, leading to the Achaean War.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The Romans under Lucius Mummius defeated the Achaeans at the Battle of Corinth, razed Corinth and dissolved the League, finally putting an end to the independence of Ancient Greece from external rule and ushering in the Roman era.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Griffith has written that Achaean War was "a hopeless enterprise for the Achaeans, badly led and backed by no adequate reserves of money or men." Lucius Mummius received the agnomen *Achaicus* ("conqueror of Achaea") for his role.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The original name Koinon of Achaeans (Achaean League) continues to exist in epigraphy, denoting either the previous Peloponnesian members (see koinon of Free Laconians) or the whole of Roman Achaea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] 120 BC Achaeans of cities in the Peloponnese dedicated an honorary inscription to Olympian Zeus, after a military expedition with Gnaeus Domitius against the Galatians in Gallia Transalpina.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The government of the league consisted of an assembly of citizens, a smaller council, and a *strategos* (general).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The *strategos* (general) controlled the league's military forces.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Originally, two *strategoi* held office simultaneously, but from 251, there was only one, who was elected annually by the assembly.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Until 217 the *strategos* entered office in May; afterwards he assumed power at the beginning of winter.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Individuals could hold the office more than once (and frequently did so), but not in consecutive years.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The general was assisted in his duties by a board of ten *demiourgoi*, a secretary, a *hipparch* (cavalry commander), a *navarch* (admiral), and *hypostrategoi* (sub-generals commanding in military districts).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The office of *Hegemon* (leader) was given to various Antigonid and Ptolemaic kings at various points in Achaean history.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Ostensibly, the *hegemon* had ultimate command on land and sea, but in fact the office seems to have been an honorary position which obliged the holder to contribute money to the League and support the League's military ventures.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Ultimate decision-making power rested with the assembly (*synodos*), which was held at Aegium four times a year.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] All male citizens of communities belonging to the League were entitled to attend.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Alongside the assembly there was a council (*boule*), which was open to citizen men over thirty years old.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Special meetings (*synkletoi*) had to be called in order for the league to declare war, form an alliance, or receive official communications from the Macedonian king or (later) the Roman Republic.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The league was ostensibly a democracy, but control seems to have consistently rested with a small elite group who monopolised the generalship and other official positions.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Given the difficulty of travelling to Aegium, assemblies were probably dominated by the wealthy.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The Achaean army was an army of the traditional *hoplite* type.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] From the 270s onwards however, much like the rest of Greece, the emergence of the shield known as the *thyreos* was incorporated into Greek warfare and a new type of troop was developed.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Reforming their troops into *thyreophoroi*, the Achaean army was now composed of light troops.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The *thyreophoroi* were a mixture of evolved *peltasts* and light *hoplites*, carrying the *thureos* shield, a thrusting spear and javelins.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Plutarch says that they could be effective at a distance, but in close combat the narrow *thureos* shield disadvantaged them.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] He also says that their formation was ineffective, because it lacked inter-locked shields or a 'leveled line of spears'.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Aratus, one of the major Achaean *strategoi* (generals) and statesmen was known for his use of light forces for irregular operations, a type of warfare suited to the *thyreophoroi* but not suited to operations in the open field.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The League in 217 decided to maintain a standing force of 8,000 mercenary foot and 500 mercenary cavalry, added to a picked citizen force of 3,000 infantry and 300 cavalry, of which 500 foot and 50 horse would come from Argos and the same amount from Megalopolis.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Aratus also obtained 500 foot and 50 horse each from Taurion and the Messenians for defence of parts of the League open to attack via Laconia.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The citizen infantry would have been armed as *thyreophoroi*, apart from the citizen light troops who would have been archers and slingers etc.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] This picked citizen force may well have existed before these so-called reforms, at least on an official basis, as we know of a similar elite force of the same size at the Battle of Sellasia in 222.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] However, it was the Achaean general Philopoemen in 208 who changed the Achaean fighting style and weaponry to the Macedonian fashion.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] According to Plutarch, Philopoemen 'persuaded them to adopt long pike and heavy shield instead of spear and buckler, to protect their bodies with helmets and breastplates and greaves, and to practice stationary and steadfast fighting instead of the nimble movements of light-armed troops'.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] These 'reforms' were not necessarily new to some of the constituent cities of the League, as the city of Megalopolis had been given bronze shields and armed in the Macedonian fashion by Antigonus Doson for the Sellasia campaign many years before.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Philopoemen then trained the new army how to fight with the new weapons and tactics and how to co-ordinate them with a new mercenary corps that was hired.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] He spent nearly 8 months of his term as *strategos* visiting, training and advising cities in this capacity.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] At the Battle of Mantinea in 207 BC the Achaean phalanx was positioned with intervals between the companies with lighter troops.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] This was a major attempt by Philopoemen to increase the flexibility of his phalanx.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] He may have picked up this tactic too from his experience at the Battle of Sellasia, where the phalanx of Antigonus Doson was also divided up with light/medium troops in between them.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] As well as reforming and re-organizing the infantry, Philopoemen also reformed the citizen cavalry.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The cavalry was recruited, much like in other Greek states, from the rich and noble classes.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Philopoemen organized the cavalry in *lochoi*, which usually in ancient military treatises means 'files', most probably of 8 men, grouped into *dilochiai*, a formation of double-files of 16 and so forth.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] However, by the time of the Achaean War in 146 BC, the League's army had decreased in strength and efficiency.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The League was even reduced to freeing and arming 12,000 slaves.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] This was probably due to the 2nd century BC decline in population.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] This may well account for the increased hiring of mercenaries, especially Cretans and Thracians.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The below are the original Peloponnesian members, except the ancient regions of Sparta, Elis and Messenia.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Later Hypana in Elis, Corone, Messene, Sparta and Pagae in Attica were joined by conquest.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] In 223 BC, Megara in Attica deserted the Achaean League and joined the Boeotian Confederacy.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Besides many city-states on the Mainland joining the Achaean Federation, certain Mediterranean island city-states also became part of the federation.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] For example, Kydonia on Crete joined at some time after 219 BC.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The city of Helike had been an important member of the first Achaean League, but sank into the sea following a disastrous earthquake in 373 BC.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The town of Olenus, also one of the twelve members of the first Achaean League, had been abandoned before 280 BC, but was sometimes counted as though still extant.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] The dates in brackets indicate the year of first adhesion.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/achaean-league] Some cities had periods of separation or foreign occupation and later joined again.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The **Aegean Sea** is an elongated embayment of the Mediterranean Sea between Europe and Asia.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] It is located between the Balkans and Anatolia, and covers an area of some 215,000 km2 (83,000 sq mi).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] In the north, the Aegean is connected to the Marmara Sea, which in turn connects to the Black Sea, by the straits of the Dardanelles and the Bosphorus, respectively.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands are located within the sea and some bound it on its southern periphery, including Crete and Rhodes.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The sea reaches a maximum depth of 2,639 m (8,658 ft) to the west of Karpathos.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Thracian Sea and the Sea of Crete are main subdivisions of the Aegean Sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands can be divided into several island groups, including the Dodecanese, the Cyclades, the Sporades, the Saronic islands and the North Aegean Islands, as well as Crete and its surrounding islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Dodecanese, located to the southeast, includes the islands of Rhodes, Kos, and Patmos; the islands of Delos and Naxos are within the Cyclades to the south of the sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Lesbos is part of the North Aegean Islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Euboea, the second-largest island in Greece, is located in the Aegean, despite being administered as part of Central Greece.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Nine out of twelve of the Administrative regions of Greece border the sea, along with the Turkish provinces of Edirne, Çanakkale, Balıkesir, İzmir, Aydın and Muğla to the east of the sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Various Turkish islands in the sea are Imbros, Tenedos, Cunda Island, and the Foça Islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea has been historically important, especially regarding the civilization of Ancient Greece, which inhabited the area around the coast of the Aegean and the Aegean islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Aegean islands facilitated contact between the people of the area and between Europe and Asia.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Along with the Greeks, Thracians lived along the northern coasts.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Romans conquered the area under the Roman Empire, and later the Byzantine Empire held it against advances by the First Bulgarian Empire.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Fourth Crusade weakened Byzantine control of the area, and it was eventually conquered by the Ottoman Empire, with the exception of Crete, which was a Venetian colony until 1669.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Greek War of Independence allowed a Greek state on the coast of the Aegean from 1829 onwards.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire held a presence over the sea for over 500 years until it was replaced by modern Turkey.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The rocks making up the floor of the Aegean are mainly limestone, though often greatly altered by volcanic activity that has convulsed the region in relatively recent geologic times.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Of particular interest are the richly colored sediments in the region of the islands of Santorini and Milos, in the south Aegean.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Notable cities on the Aegean coastline include Athens, Thessaloniki, Heraklion, Volos, Alexandroupolis and Kavala in Greece, and İzmir and Bodrum in Turkey.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Several issues concerning sovereignty within the Aegean Sea are disputed between Greece and Turkey.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Aegean dispute has had a large effect on Greece-Turkey relations since the 1970s.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Issues include the delimitation of territorial waters, national airspace, exclusive economic zones, and flight information regions.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Ancient Greek authors also called it the "Greek Sea".
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The sea was known in Latin as *Mare Aegaeum* while under the control of the Roman Empire.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Pliny the Elder write that the Romans used the terms "Macedonian" for the northern part near Macedonia and Thrace provinces, and "Grecian" for the part near Greece itself.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] In medieval Latin, the Aegean Sea was known as *Egeopelagus*, a form attested as late as 1419 in Venetian state papers (Ducatus Egeopelagi) and derived from the Greek αἰγαιοπέλαγος / αἰγαῖον πέλαγος.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The term *Arcipelago* also appears, for instance in a treaty on 30 June 1268 between the Venetians and the emperor Michael Palaeologus.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] This term subsequently gave rise to *Archipelago* (Greek: αρχιπέλαγος), which in many European languages originally referred specifically to the Aegean Sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The terms *Greek Archipelago* or *Grecian Archipelago* were also used.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Later, as archipelago came to be used increasingly as a generic term for island-studded seas, the terms Greek Archipelago or Grecian Archipelago continued to be used alongside the ancient name, Aegean Sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] In some South Slavic languages, the Aegean is called *White Sea* (Bulgarian: Бяло море, romanized: *Byalo more*; Macedonian: Бело море, romanized: *Belo more*; Serbian: *Belo more* / Бело море).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Turkish name for the sea is *Ege Denizi*, which is derived from the Greek name, and *Adalar Denizi* meaning "Sea of Islands".
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] In the past, Turks also referred to it as the "White Sea", to differentiate it from the Black Sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea is an elongated embayment of the Mediterranean Sea and covers about 214,000 square kilometres (83,000 sq mi) in area, measuring about 670 kilometres (420 mi) longitudinally and 390 kilometres (240 mi) latitudinal.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The sea's maximum depth is 2,639 metres (8,658 ft), located at a point west of Karpathos.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands are found within its waters, with the following islands delimiting the sea on the south, generally from west to east: Kythera, Antikythera, Crete, Kasos, Karpathos and Rhodes.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Anatolian peninsula marks the eastern boundary of the sea, while the Greek mainland marks the west.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Several seas are contained within the Aegean Sea; the Thracian Sea is a section of the Aegean located to the north, the Icarian Sea to the east, the Myrtoan Sea to the west, while the Sea of Crete is the southern section.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Greek regions that border the sea, in alphabetical order, are Attica, Central Greece, Central Macedonia, Crete, Eastern Macedonia and Thrace, North Aegean, Peloponnese, South Aegean, and Thessaly.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The traditional Greek region of Macedonia also borders the sea, to the north.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Many of the Aegean islands or island chains, are geographical extensions of the mountains on the mainland.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] One chain extends across the sea to Chios, another extends across Euboea to Samos, and a third extends across the Peloponnese and Crete to Rhodes, dividing the Aegean from the Mediterranean.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea is connected to the Sea of Marmara by the Dardanelles, also known from Classical Antiquity as the Hellespont.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Dardanelles are located to the northeast of the sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] It ultimately connects with the Black Sea through the Bosporus strait, upon which lies the city of Istanbul.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Dardanelles and the Bosporus are known as the Turkish Straits.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Aegean surface water circulates in a counterclockwise gyre, with hypersaline Mediterranean water moving northward along the west coast of Turkey, before being displaced by less dense Black Sea outflow.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The dense Mediterranean water sinks below the Black Sea inflow to a depth of 23–30 metres (75–98 ft), then flows through the Dardanelles Strait and into the Sea of Marmara at velocities of 5–15 cm/s (2–6 in/s).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Black Sea outflow moves westward along the northern Aegean Sea, then flows southwards along the east coast of Greece.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The physical oceanography of the Aegean Sea is controlled mainly by the regional climate, the fresh water discharge from major rivers draining southeastern Europe, and the seasonal variations in the Black Sea surface water outflow through the Dardanelles Strait.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The climate of the Aegean Sea largely reflects the climate of Greece and Western Turkey, which is to say, predominantly Mediterranean.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] According to the Köppen climate classification, most of the Aegean is classified as Hot-summer Mediterranean (*Csa*), with hotter and drier summers along with milder and wetter winters.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] However, high temperatures during summers are generally not quite as high as those in arid or semiarid climates due to the presence of a large body of water.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] This is most predominant in the west and east coasts of the Aegean, and within the Aegean islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] In the north of the Aegean Sea, the climate is instead classified as Cold semi-arid *(BSk)*, which feature cooler summers than Hot-summer Mediterranean climates.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Etesian winds are a dominant weather influence in the Aegean Basin.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Numerous Greek and Turkish settlements are located along their mainland coast, as well as on towns on the Aegean islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The largest cities are Athens and Thessaloniki in Greece and İzmir in Turkey.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The most populated of the Aegean islands is Crete, followed by Euboea and Rhodes.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Greece has established several marine protected areas along its coasts.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] According to the Network of Managers of Marine Protected Areas in the Mediterranean (MedPAN), four Greek MPAs are participating in the Network.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] These include Alonnisos Marine Park, while the Missolonghi–Aitoliko Lagoons and the island of Zakynthos are not on the Aegean.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The current coastline dates back to about 4000 BC.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Before that time, at the peak of the last ice age (about 18,000 years ago) sea levels everywhere were 130 metres (430 ft) lower, and there were large well-watered coastal plains instead of much of the northern Aegean.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] When they were first occupied, the present-day islands including Milos with its important obsidian production were probably still connected to the mainland.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The present coastal arrangement appeared around 9,000 years ago, with post-ice age sea levels continuing to rise for another 3,000 years after that.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The subsequent Bronze Age civilizations of Greece and the Aegean Sea have given rise to the general term *Aegean civilization*.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] In ancient times, the sea was the birthplace of two ancient civilizations – the Minoans of Crete and the Mycenaeans of the Peloponnese.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Minoan civilization was a Bronze Age civilization on the island of Crete and other Aegean islands, flourishing from around 3000 to 1450 BC before a period of decline, finally ending at around 1100 BC.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] It represented the first advanced civilization in Europe, leaving behind massive building complexes, tools, stunning artwork, writing systems, and a massive network of trade.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Minoan period saw extensive trade between Crete, Aegean, and Mediterranean settlements, particularly the Near East.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The most notable Minoan palace is that of Knossos, followed by that of Phaistos.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Mycenaean Greeks arose on the mainland, becoming the first advanced civilization in mainland Greece, which lasted from approximately 1600 to 1100 BC.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] It is believed that the site of Mycenae, which sits close to the Aegean coast, was the center of Mycenaean civilization.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Mycenaeans introduced several innovations in the fields of engineering, architecture and military infrastructure, while trade over vast areas of the Mediterranean, including the Aegean, was essential for the Mycenaean economy.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Their syllabic script, the Linear B, offers the first written records of the Greek language and their religion already included several deities that can also be found in the Olympic Pantheon.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Mycenaean Greece was dominated by a warrior elite society and consisted of a network of palace-centered states that developed rigid hierarchical, political, social and economic systems.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] At the head of this society was the king, known as *wanax*.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The civilization of Mycenaean Greeks perished with the collapse of Bronze Age culture in the eastern Mediterranean, to be followed by the so-called Greek Dark Ages.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] It is undetermined what cause the collapse of the Mycenaeans.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] During the Greek Dark Ages, writing in the Linear B script ceased, vital trade links were lost, and towns and villages were abandoned.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Archaic period followed the Greek Dark Ages in the 8th century BC.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Greece became divided into small self-governing communities, and adopted the Phoenician alphabet, modifying it to create the Greek alphabet.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] By the 6th century BC several cities had emerged as dominant in Greek affairs: Athens, Sparta, Corinth, and Thebes, of which Athens, Sparta, and Corinth were closest to the Aegean Sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Each of them had brought the surrounding rural areas and smaller towns under their control, and Athens and Corinth had become major maritime and mercantile powers as well.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] In the 8th and 7th centuries BC many Greeks migrated to form colonies in Magna Graecia (Southern Italy and Sicily), Asia Minor and further afield.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea was the setting for one of the most pivotal naval engagements in history, when, on 20 September 480 B.C., the Athenian fleet gained a decisive victory over the Persian fleet of the Xerxes II of Persia at the Battle of Salamis.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Thus ending any further attempt of western expansion by the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea would later come to be under the control, albeit briefly, of the Kingdom of Macedonia.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Philip II and his son Alexander the Great led a series of conquests that led not only to the unification of the Greek mainland and the control of the Aegean Sea under his rule, but also the destruction of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] After Alexander the Great's death, his empire was divided among his generals.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Cassander became king of the Hellenistic kingdom of Macedon, which held territory along the western coast of the Aegean, roughly corresponding to modern-day Greece.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Kingdom of Lysimachus had control over the sea's eastern coast.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Greece had entered the Hellenistic period.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Macedonian Wars were a series of conflicts fought by the Roman Republic and its Greek allies in the eastern Mediterranean against several different major Greek kingdoms.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] They resulted in Roman control or influence over the eastern Mediterranean basin, including the Aegean, in addition to their hegemony in the western Mediterranean after the Punic Wars.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] During Roman rule, the land around the Aegean Sea fell under the provinces of Achaea, Macedonia, Thracia, Asia and Creta et Cyrenaica (island of Crete).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The fall of the Western Roman Empire allowed its successor state, the Byzantine Empire, to continue Roman control over the Aegean Sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] However, their territory would later be threatened by the early Muslim conquests initiated by Muhammad in the 7th century.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Although the Rashidun Caliphate did not manage to obtain land along the coast of the Aegean Sea, its conquest of the Eastern Anatolian peninsula as well as Egypt, the Levant, and North Africa left the Byzantine Empire weakened.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Umayyad Caliphate expanded the territorial gains of the Rashidun Caliphate, conquering much of North Africa, and threatened the Byzantine Empire's control of Western Anatolia, where it meets the Aegean Sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] During the 820s, Crete was conquered by a group of Berbers Andalusians exiles led by Abu Hafs Umar al-Iqritishi, and it became an independent Islamic state.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Byzantine Empire launched a campaign that took most of the island back in 842 and 843 under Theoktistos, but the re-conquest was not completed and was soon reversed.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Later attempts by the Byzantine Empire to recover the island were without success.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] For the approximately 135 years of its existence, the emirate of Crete was one of the major foes of Byzantium.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Crete commanded the sea lanes of the Eastern Mediterranean and functioned as a forward base and haven for Muslim corsair fleets that ravaged the Byzantine-controlled shores of the Aegean Sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Crete returned to Byzantine rule under Nikephoros II Phokas, who launched a huge campaign against the Emirate of Crete in 960 to 961.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Meanwhile, the Bulgarian Empire threatened Byzantine control of Northern Greece and the Aegean coast to the south.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Under Presian and his successor Boris I, the Bulgarian Empire managed to obtain a small portion of the northern Aegean coast.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Simeon I of Bulgaria led Bulgaria to its greatest territorial expansion, and managed to conqueror much of the northern and western coasts of the Aegean.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Second Bulgarian Empire achieved similar success along, again, the northern and western coasts, under Ivan Asen II of Bulgaria.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Seljuk Turks, under the Seljuk Empire, invaded the Byzantine Empire in 1068, from which they annexed almost all the territories of Anatolia, including the east coast of the Aegean Sea, during the reign of Alp Arslan, the second Sultan of the Seljuk Empire.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] After the death of his successor, Malik Shah I, the empire was divided, and Malik Shah was succeeded in Anatolia by Kilij Arslan I, who founded the Sultanate of Rum.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Byzantines yet again recaptured the eastern coast of the Aegean.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Venetians created the maritime state of the Duchy of the Archipelago, which included all the Cyclades except Mykonos and Tinos.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Empire of Nicaea, a Byzantine rump state, managed to affect the Recapture of Constantinople from the Latins in 1261 and defeat Epirus.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Byzantine successes were not to last; the Ottomans would conquer the area around the Aegean coast, but before their expansion the Byzantine Empire had already been weakened from internal conflict.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] By the late 14th century, the Byzantine Empire had lost all control of the coast of the Aegean Sea and could only exercise power around their capital, Constantinople.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire then gained control of all the Aegean coast with the exception of Crete, which was a Venetian colony until 1669.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Greek War of Independence allowed a Greek state on the coast of the Aegean from 1829 onward.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] In the aftermath of the Balkan Wars (1912–1913) Greece expanded northwards along the coast, while Bulgaria gained access in the northernmost section of the sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire held a presence over the sea for over 500 years until its dissolution following World War I, when it was replaced by modern Turkey.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] After the war, Greece gained control over the area around the northern coast of the Aegean, including the territory held by Bulgaria.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] By the 1920s, Greece and Turkey had about resumed their present-day borders.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] In the Italo-Turkish War of 1912, Italy captured the Dodecanese islands, and had occupied them since, reneging on the 1919 Venizelos–Tittoni agreement to cede them to Greece.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Greco-Italian War took place from October 1940 to April 1941 as part of the Balkans Campaign of World War II.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Italian war aim was to establish a Greek puppet state, which would permit the Italian annexation of the Sporades and Cyclades islands in the Aegean Sea, to be administered as a part of the Italian Aegean Islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The German invasion resulted in the Axis occupation of Greece.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The German troops evacuated Athens on 12 October 1944, and by the end of the month, they had withdrawn from mainland Greece.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Greece was then liberated by Allied troops.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Many of the islands in the Aegean have safe harbours and bays.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] In ancient times, navigation through the sea was easier than travelling across the rough terrain of the Greek mainland, and to some extent, the coastal areas of Anatolia.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Many of the islands are volcanic, and marble and iron are mined on other islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The larger islands have some fertile valleys and plains.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Of the main islands in the Aegean Sea, two belong to Turkey – Bozcaada (Tenedos) and Gökçeada (Imbros); the rest belong to Greece.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Between the two countries, there are political disputes over several aspects of political control over the Aegean space, including the size of territorial waters, air control and the delimitation of economic rights to the continental shelf.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] These issues are known as the Aegean dispute.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Multiple ports are located along the Greek and Turkish coasts of the Aegean Sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The port of Piraeus in Athens is the chief port in Greece, the largest passenger port in Europe and the third largest in the world, servicing about 20 million passengers annually.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] With a throughput of 1.4 million TEUs, Piraeus is placed among the top ten ports in container traffic in Europe and the top container port in the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Piraeus is also the commercial hub of Greek shipping.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Piraeus bi-annually acts as the focus for a major shipping convention, known as Posidonia, which attracts maritime industry professionals from all over the world.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Piraeus is currently Greece's third-busiest port in terms of tons of goods transported, behind Agioi Theodoroi and Thessaloniki.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The central port serves ferry routes to almost every island in the eastern portion of Greece, the island of Crete, the Cyclades, the Dodecanese, and much of the northern and the eastern Aegean Sea, while the western part of the port is used for cargo services.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] As of 2007, the Port of Thessaloniki was the second-largest container port in Greece after the port of Piraeus, making it one of the busiest ports in Greece.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] In 2007, the Port of Thessaloniki handled 14,373,245 tonnes of cargo and 222,824 TEU's.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Paloukia, on the island of Salamis, is a major passenger port.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Fish are Greece's second-largest agricultural export, and Greece has Europe's largest fishing fleet.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Fish captured include sardines, mackerel, grouper, grey mullets, sea bass, and seabream.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] There is a considerable difference between fish catches between the pelagic and demersal zones; with respect to pelagic fisheries, the catches from the northern, central and southern Aegean area groupings are dominated, respectively, by anchovy, horse mackerels, and boops.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] For demersal fisheries, the catches from the northern and southern Aegean area groupings are dominated by grey mullets and pickerel (*Spicara smaris*) respectively.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The industry has been impacted by the Great Recession.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Overfishing and habitat destruction is also a concern, threatening grouper, and seabream populations, resulting in perhaps a 50% decline of fish catch.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] To address these concerns, Greek fishermen have been offered a compensation by the government.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Although some species are defined as protected or threatened under EU legislation, several illegal species such as the molluscs *Pinna nobilis*, *Charonia tritonis* and *Lithophaga lithophaga*, can be bought in restaurants and fish markets around Greece.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The Aegean islands within the Aegean Sea are significant tourist destinations.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Tourism to the Aegean islands contributes a significant portion of tourism in Greece, especially since the second half of the 20th century.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] A total of five UNESCO World Heritage sites are located the Aegean Islands; these include the Monastery of Saint John the Theologian and the Cave of the Apocalypse on Patmos, the Pythagoreion and Heraion of Samos in Samos, the Nea Moni of Chios, the island of Delos, and the Medieval City of Rhodes.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Greece is one of the most visited countries in Europe and the world with over 33 million visitors in 2018, and the tourism industry around a quarter of Greece's Gross Domestic Product.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The islands of Santorini, Crete, Lesbos, Delos, and Mykonos are common tourist destinations.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] An estimated 2 million tourists visit Santorini annually.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] However, concerns relating to overtourism have arisen in recent years, such as issues of inadequate infrastructure and overcrowding.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Alongside Greece, Turkey has also been successful in developing resort areas and attracting large number of tourists, contributing to tourism in Turkey.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The phrase "Blue Cruise" refers to recreational voyages along the Turkish Riviera, including across the Aegean.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The ancient city of Troy, a World Heritage Site, is on the Turkish coast of the Aegean.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Greece and Turkey both take part in the Blue Flag beach certification programme of the Foundation for Environmental Education.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] The certification is awarded for beaches and marinas meeting strict quality standards including environmental protection, water quality, safety and services criteria.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] As of 2015, the Blue Flag has been awarded to 395 beaches and 9 marinas in Greece.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aegean-sea] Southern Aegean beaches on the Turkish coast include Muğla, with 102 beaches awarded with the blue flag, along with İzmir and Aydın, who have 49 and 30 beaches awarded respectively.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The islands' inhabitants are known as Aeolians (Italian: *Eoliani*).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The islands had a permanent population of 14,224 at the 2011 census; the latest official estimate is 15,419 as of 1 January 2019.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The Aeolian Islands are a popular tourist destination in the summer and attract up to 600,000 visitors annually.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] There are seven significant islands: Lipari, Vulcano, Salina, Stromboli, Filicudi, Alicudi and Panarea, and a set of minor islands and rocks.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The Aeolian Islands are 30 to 80 kilometres (19 to 50 mi) off the north coast of Sicily in the Tyrrhenian Sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Vulcano is located closest to the Sicilian coast.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Lipari and Salina follow to the north, Filicudi and Alicudi to the west, and Panarea and Stromboli to the northeast.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] In addition to these seven inhabited islands, there are a number of smaller, uninhabited islands and rocky cliffs, such as Basiluzzo, Strombolicchio, Dattilo and Lisca Bianca.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The smallest inhabited island, at 3.4 km2 (1.3 mi2), is Panarea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The highest elevation of the Lipari Islands is Monte Fossa delle Felci on Salina, which reaches a height of 962 m (3,156 ft).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The seven Aeolian Islands, covering an area of 1,600 km2 (620 sq mi), originated in the Tyrrhenian Basin, a great plain at the bottom of the Tyrrhenian Sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Emissions of lava from depths of up to 3,600 m (11,800 ft) resulted in the formation of the Aeolian Islands, together with Ustica and a series of submarine volcanoes named Magnani, Vavilov, Marsili and Palinuro, as well as two that are unnamed.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The present shape of the Aeolian Islands is the result of volcanic activity over a period of 260,000 years.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] There are two active volcanoes – Stromboli and Vulcano.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Steaming fumaroles and thermal waters are on most of the islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The volcanic activity has also left the islands with a very fertile soil that is beneficial in the growth of natural flora.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Geologically the archipelago is defined as a volcanic arc.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The origin of the Aeolian Islands is due to movement of the Earth's crust as a result of plate tectonics.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The African continental shelf is in constant movement towards Europe.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Its subduction underneath the Eurasian plate generates magma, which rises to the surface to form the volcanoes.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The "Aeolian Arc" extends for more than 140 km (87 mi).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] It is a section of a larger area of geological instability across the Mediterranean region, caused by the collision of Africa and Europe, which includes Sicily, Calabria, and Campania together with Greece and the Aegean islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The islands form part of the Sicilian Metropolitan City of Messina.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] All the islands except Salina comprise the *comune* of Lipari within that province; Salina forms three separate *comunes*: Malfa, Leni and Santa Marina Salina.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Curbing urban development has been a key in preserving the Aeolian islands in a natural state.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Existing residences can be bought and restored but they must be constructed to resemble its whitewashed houses.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Traditional houses consist of modular cubes constructed from indigenous building materials like stone, lava, pumice, and tufo.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Almost all houses have a huge outdoor terrace, usually shaded by grape and flowering vines.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] In Homer's epic poem, the Odyssey, Aeolus, son of Hippotes, was the divine keeper of the winds and king of the mythical, floating island of Aeolia.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] He kept the violent winds locked safely away inside the interior of his isle, releasing them only at the command of greater gods to wreak devastation upon the world.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The hero of the epic poem, Odysseus, on his travels to return home from Troy, visited Aeolus' isle and was entrusted with a bag containing all of the winds to ensure a safe voyage home.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] However, during the trip, the hero's companions opened the bag and the escaping winds carried their ship all the way back to Aeolus' shore.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The first evidence of Sicilian migration was in Lipari (Castellaro Vecchio culture).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The manufacture and commerce of obsidian objects was highly developed until the introduction of metals.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] During the Bronze Age, the Aeolians prospered by means of maritime commerce in an area which extended from Mycenae to the British Isles, from where tin was imported.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Villages on the Aeolian islands flourished on Capo Graziano (Filicudi), Castello (Lipari), Serro dei Cianfi (Salina), Capo Milazzese (Panarea), and Portella (Salina).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] All these settlements were destroyed by new Italic invasions in 1250 BC.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] According to Diodorus Siculus, the Aeolian Islands were occupied by the Ausones led by Liparus.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Liparus was succeeded by Aeolus whose house, according to the *Odyssey* by Homer, gave hospitality to Odysseus.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] In 580 BC, Greeks exiled from Rhodes and Knidos landed at Lipari and began a period of Greek domination, which was known for acts of piracy against Etruscan and Phoenician shipping.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] There was production of vases and other ceramics.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The islanders were allies of the Carthaginians against Rome during the Punic Wars.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Although the Battle of the Lipari Islands in 260 BC led to a Carthaginian victory, the Romans later sacked Lipari and their domination led to a period of poverty.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] At the fall of the Western Roman Empire, the Aeolian Islands came under the sway of the Visigoths, the Vandals and the Ostrogoths, followed by the domination of the Byzantine Empire.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] According to a Christian legend, in 264 a coffin which contained the body of Bartholomew washed up on the beach of Lipari, with the result that Bartholomew was immediately elected the patron saint of the Aeolian Islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] In 836 the Aghlabids of Ziyadat Allah I of Ifriqiya sacked Lipari, massacred most of the population, enslaved the survivors and annexed the Liparian Islands into the Emirate of Sicily.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The Norman conquest of Sicily from the Emirate of Sicily in 1061 resulted in the annexation of the islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Roger II of Sicily sent the Benedictine monks to Lipari, which gave rise to considerable development on the islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] A cathedral dedicated to Saint Bartholomew was built, as well as the Benedictine monastery in the castle.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] In 1208 Frederick II of Swabia acceded to the throne of the Kingdom of Sicily.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The period of prosperity which followed, ended with the domination of the Angevins and the rebellion of the Sicilians which culminated in the revolt of the Sicilian Vespers.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The Aeolians however, remained loyal to Charles of Anjou, and commercial links were established with Naples, the capital of the Angevin kingdom.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] In 1337 Lipari opened its gates to the French fleet without resistance, and in return obtained various commercial and fiscal benefits.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] In the mid-15th century, Naples and Palermo united into the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies under the crown of Alfonso V of Aragon.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] On June 30, 1544, a fleet of 180 Ottoman vessels under the command of the corsair Hayreddin Barbarossa occupied Lipari and laid siege to the castle.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Historically, it is said around 9,000 of the 10,000 citizens of Lipari were captured and enslaved although a couple of more recent scholars have questioned this number arguing for a lower population at the time of Barbarossa.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] A number of citizens were ransomed in Messina and returned to the islands but most of those captured never returned.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Only after the tragedy did the Spanish authorities turn their attention to Lipari and repopulate the city with Sicilian, Calabrian and Spanish families.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The city walls and houses were rebuilt and an Aeolian fleet was constructed which was able to successfully defend the Tyrrhenian Sea from the Ottomans.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] In 1693, an earthquake destroyed all the towns in eastern Sicily, causing around 60,000 deaths.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] After the population invoked the protection of Saint Bartholomew during prayers in the cathedral, there was not a single victim on the Aeolian Islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The economic conditions of the islands improved greatly during the 17th century with agricultural progress (malvasia grapes), capers, and a variety of fruit, vegetables and fishing).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] With the Bourbons came the introduction of criminal and political prisoners to the islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] In 1916, the penal colony was closed, but the Fascist regime unsuccessfully tried to reopen it in 1926.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The island population reacted by pulling down the remains of the ex-penitentiary in the castle.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] However, not long after, the castle was converted to accommodate anti-Fascist political prisoners in enforced exile.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Liparians fraternised with these exiles until the Allies' liberation.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] After the war, the same room that had housed the opponents of Fascism became the Aeolian Archaeological Museum.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Towards the end of the 19th century, the Aeolian Islands were visited by Archduke Ludwig Salvator of Austria—a friend of the islands and also a man with a profound knowledge of the archipelago.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Between the years 1893–96 he published a work of eight volumes on the Aeolian Islands.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] In August 1888, the crater named Fossa on Vulcano erupted and caused many deaths in the sulphur mines.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] On New Year's Day in 1909, a rumour appeared in international newspapers that the Aeolian Islands had been "swallowed up by the sea" during a time of volcanic activity.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] While communication with the islands was interrupted for a time, they were not otherwise inconvenienced.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] During World War II, all of the Aeolian Islands were captured by the Allies in August 1943, during the invasion of Sicily.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The islands were then extensively searched by archeologists Madeleine Cavalier and Luigi Bernabò Brea after World War II.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] The Aeolian Islands were listed by UNESCO in 2000 as a World Heritage Site for providing "an outstanding record of volcanic island-building and destruction, and ongoing volcanic phenomena".
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] Status as a World Heritage Site was threatened by Italy's failure to close the pumice quarry as well as its failure to prevent the building of 4 new harbours.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolian-islands] However, as of 2020, it is still listed by UNESCO as a World Heritage site.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] The Aeolic dialect shows many archaisms in comparison to the other Ancient Greek dialects (Arcadocypriot, Attic, Ionic, and Doric), as well as many innovations; it is, consequently, considered to be—for the modern reader—perhaps the most difficult of the dialects.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Aeolic Greek is widely known as the language of Sappho and of Alcaeus of Mytilene.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Aeolic poetry, which is exemplified in the works of Sappho, mostly uses four classical meters known as the Aeolics: Glyconic (the most basic form of Aeolic line), hendecasyllabic verse, Sapphic stanza, and Alcaic stanza (the latter two are respectively named for Sappho and Alcaeus).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Other scholars have suggested an Aeolic Greek classification with strong Northwest Greek influence for the ancient Macedonian dialect.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Hellanicus of Lesbos considered Makedon to be a son of Aeolus (son of Hellen).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Proto-Indo-European and Proto-Greek **kʷ* changed to Aeolic *p* everywhere.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] By contrast, PIE **kʷ* changed to Attic/Ionic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric *t* before *e* and *i*.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Similarly PIE/PGk **gʷ* always became *b* and PIE **gʷʰ* > PGk **kʰʷ* always became *ph* (whereas in other dialects they became alternating *b*/*d* and *ph*/*th* before back/front vowels).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Labiovelars were treated the same way in the P-Celtic languages and the Sabellic languages.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] A Proto-Greek consonant cluster with *h* (from Indo-European **s*) and a sonorant (*r, l, n, m, w, y*) changed to the double sonorant (*rr, ll, nn, mm, ww, yy*) in Lesbian and Thessalian (sub-dialects of Aeolic) by assimilation.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] In Attic/Ionic, Doric, and Boeotian Aeolic, the *h* assimilated to the vowel before the consonant cluster, causing the vowel to lengthen by compensatory lengthening.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Lesbian Aeolic lost initial *h-* (*psilosis* "stripping") from Proto-Indo-European *s- or *y-.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] By contrast, Ionic sometimes retains it, and Attic always retains it.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] In Thessalian and Boeotian (sub-dialects of Aeolic) and Doric, the Proto-Indo-European and Proto-Greek semi-vowel *w* (digamma) was retained at the beginning of a word.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] In Aeolic and Doric, Proto-Greek long *ā* remains.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] By contrast, in Attic, long *ā* changes to long *ē* in most cases; in Ionic, it changes everywhere.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Compensatory lengthening of *a, e, o* in Lesbian gives *ai, ei, oi* (in Attic, it would be *ā, ei, ou*) for example in the accusative plural of a and o stem nouns, or in many 3 Pl verb conjugations.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] In Boeotian, the vowel-system was, in many cases, changed in a way reminiscent of the modern Greek pronunciation.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] In Lesbian Aeolic, the accent of all words is recessive (*barytonesis*), as is typical only in the verbs of other dialects.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Contracted or vowel-stem verbs that are thematic in Attic/Ionic are often athematic (*-mi*) in Aeolic.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Aeolic athematic infinitive active ends in *-men* or (Lesbian) *-menai*. ~ Attic/Ionic has *-enai*.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] In the Lesbian dialect this ending also extends to the thematic conjugation, where Attic/Ionic has *-ein*.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] All three of these Aeolic endings occur in Homer.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Proto-Greek *-ans* and *-ons* → *-ais* and *-ois* (first- and second declension accusative plural) ~ Attic/Ionic -*ās* and *-ōs* (-ους).
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Dative plural *-aisi* and *-oisi* ~ Attic/Ionic *-ais* and *-ois*.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] The participle has *-ois* and *-ais* for Attic *-ōs* (-ους), *-ās*.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Below is a list of several words in the Aeolian dialect, written in the Greek alphabet, along with a transcription in the Latin alphabet.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] Each word is followed by its meaning and compared to similar words in other ancient Greek dialects.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/aeolic-greek] The "notes" section provides additional information, and if applicable, an etymology is given.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] Apollonia became autonomous from Cyrene at latest by the time the area came within the power of Rome, when it was one of the five cities of the Libyan Pentapolis, growing in power until, in the 6th century AD, it became the capital of the Roman province of Libya Superior or Libya Pentapolitana.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] The city became known as **Sozusa**, which explains the modern name of **Marsa Susa** or **Susa**, which grew up long after the cessation of urban life in the ancient city after the Arab occupation of AD 643.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] Sozusa was an episcopal see and is included in the Catholic Church's list of titular sees.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] The early foundation levels of the city of Apollonia are below sea level due to submergence in earthquakes, while the upper strata of the later Byzantine Christian periods are several meters above sea level, built on the accumulated deposits of previous periods.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] The existence of buildings in the sea was noted by Beechey (1827), with some rough drawings, and Goodchild (1950s) and André Laronde also published archaeological surveys of the site.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] In 1958 and 1959 Nicholas Flemming, then an undergraduate at Cambridge University, led teams of undergraduates trained in scuba diving and underwater surveying to map the large sector of the city beneath the sea.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] The results of this work were published, complete with maps and diagrams of underwater buildings in the references cited below.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] Carlo Beltrame and colleagues have recently made an underwater photographic survey of some of the buildings.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] The Crete earthquake and tsunami of 21 July 365 AD apparently caused extensive damage to the city and harbor.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] The Apollonia (Susa) Museum houses many artifacts found on the ancient site.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] The remains of the ancient port in Apollonia are extremely well preserved because they are underwater.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] The difference in sea level, indeed, was estimated to be around 3.70-3.80 m.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] The port is relatively early in date, dating from the 6th/7th Century BC, and this makes it unique as no other complete port is this old.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] The Palace of the Dux was excavated by Goodchild between 1959 and 1962.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] It was last used as the Byzantine Duke's Palace and contains over 100 rooms.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] A marble inscription testifies to its use as a Roman military commander's house, however the identification of the name and status of the man who built the palace is problematic.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] The well-preserved Greek theatre stands facing the sea outside the old city walls.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] This monument dates to the 3rd century BC and is therefore one of the oldest sites in Apollonia.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] The structure was modified under Domitian, suggesting its use as an arena for gladiatorial fights.
[src:apollonia-cyrenaica/apollonia-cyrenaica] The 5th century saw the abandonment of the theatre and the re-use of the columns from the stage as spolia in the eastern basilica.
